@node "Covington" "John Covington"
Brief Bio:

   I'm John Covington and I first logged on to FIDO about three years ago.
At the time I lived in Georgia.  I was a regular FIDO Amiga International
participant for about a year and a half or so until I moved to North
Carolina.  Shortly after that time things got badly screwed up somewhere in
the FIDO distribution network and I got really tired of posting and replying
only to have everything dumped to NIL:> somewhere in the network.  At this
time, though, the distribution network seems to have been repaired for the
most part so I am, at least for now, attempting to post and reply and will
do so on a fairly regular basis unless FIDO develops more black holes.

   I'm 41, happily married, and for the past four years have run a
successful small advertising house, doing ads for companies on local cable
networks.  I've owned every Amiga made except for the A1000 and the A4000T;
that is, an A500, an A2000, an A2500, an A3000, an A3000T, and now an A4000
(desk model.)  I've owned Amigas since late 1986 (or early '87--sort of runs
together.)

   My current setup is a stock A4000 with the following additions: A
FASTLANE scsi-2 controller with 16 megs fastram, another 16 megs of fastram
on the motherboard, a 1.3 gig Conner scsi-2 drive, a PAR running a .5 gig
IDE, and of course the stock 120-meg IDE that came with the A4000 (it's
worth noting here that the IDE and scsi drives and controllers function
together flawlessly and transparently in the machine); a Studio 16 (AD516);
and last but not least a Toaster running in a "Toaster Cozzy" on top of my
A4000.  My TBC's and Vectorscope and composite-to-S-VHS converter are all
housed in an adjacent reamed out clone mini-tower (slots, power and fan
only.)  I use AmiLink to control an AB-ROLL editing sytem.  I use plain-jane
switchboxes to control various serial and parallel control configurations,
as well as a small color scanner.  On the software side I guess that I have
owned and used about every major piece of Amiga software that's ever been
written.  In the work that I do I have more than once found out that 32-megs
of fastram sometimes isn't enough!

   In about a month, I'll be moving back to Georgia.

   The @{"FIDO pics" system "amigadisk6:c/vt amigadisk6:pics/john_covington.iff"} are corny but they were fun to do.

See you on the FIDO...:) (Unless the black holes again rip the fabric of our
continuum...:)....)

(ED note: wish I had the ability to see and/or convert Ham8... I have the
horrible feeling I'm losing some detail!)
@endnode

