@node "Rich Koster" "Rich & Carol Koster"
[Note: I only included the LW rendered pic, as it includes the other pic
that Rich refers to -- ED.]

                                            March 5, 1994

I'm @{"Rich Koster" system "amigadisk6:c/vt amigadisk6:pics/rich&carol_koster.iff"}, shown in the included picture having a great time at Walt
Disney World with my wife Carol, at our "Laughing Place": Splash Mountain.
I'm supplying a full-screen version of this picture, as well as another one
where I've put it inside a LightWave 3D-rendered "picture book" along with
Carol and me in another pose.  I don't know what format these pictures will
be when they are put on the Echo Pics disk, but I've provided both of them
in HAM8 formats after converting them from IFF 24 format (made in the Video
Toaster 4000) by using Art Department Pro version 2.5.0.

On the Fidonet Amiga echo I was honored to be asked by Joyce Divina to
assist her as moderator.aide, and I gladly accepted.  I've been on the echo
for about 5 years now.  I'm 40 years old, but I'm still young at heart!  ;-)
I was born on May 2, 1953.  Carol and I married on December 6, 1980.  Carol
and I don't have any kids, but we do have a 13-year-old cat named Azzie that
we treat like a child.  Azzie is short for Azalea Isadora Duncan Pele
Prytania Segner Koster.  :-)

I've been an Amiga user since March of 1988 when Carol and I bought an Amiga
500.  I was impressed with Deluxe Paint and got the Amiga to help me improve
my graphics skills.  At the time I was directing newscasts and making
graphics for them on a TV station in Mobile, Alabama. Even though I was
using a Dubner 32-bit paint box at work, I didn't have a lot of time there
to experiment with it.  There was a lot involved with being a director, and
there wasn't much time to make graphics.  So instead of spending my off time
at work and being away from my wife, I opted instead to use the Amiga at
home for graphics. My graphics skills improved and in November of that year
I was hired in a bigger city (New Orleans) creating electronic graphics
without having to also direct.

Our first Amiga was only upgraded from a stock model by increasing the RAM
to 1 meg, getting the newer Agnus chip to be able to use all of that memory
for graphics (at the cost of slowing down the machine, though), and getting
an extra 3.5" disk drive, printer and 2400 baud modem.  This setup served us
well, even when downloading echo messages and becoming a point, run totally
off of floppies!

At work I was able to use an Amiga 2000 with a Video Toaster for fun and
profit!  I created many LightWave 3D graphics and animations, as well as
simpler animations using Deluxe Paint IV.  In March of 1993 I bought my own
Amiga 4000/040 and Video Toaster 4000, with 18 megs of RAM.  What an
enjoyable difference compared to my first Amiga!  Now I very often bring my
Amiga/Toaster to the TV station to create animations for special projects,
since it shines far and above the other graphics boxes we have at work for
animation.  My graphics and animation work has appeared on the networks and
won numerous awards on the local, national, and even international level.
One year at a national convention for broadcast promotion people (PROMAX)
our station's promotion team won more gold awards there than even ABC, CBS,
or NBC!

I had the pleasure of attending the first (which turned out to also be the
last!) AmiEXPO to be held in Orlando, Florida.  The highlight for me was
taking two courses there from Amiga artist Jim Sachs, as well as learning
more about 3D graphics.

Carol and I also have attended both of the Fidonet Amiga Echo Picnics ('92 &
'93) and at this writing are looking forward to the Amiga Echo Gathering at
the New Orleans Jazz Fest in April of 1994.

I have written articles and software for JUMPDISK magazine (the original
disk magazine for the Amiga), and I've been published in Video Systems
magazine (Nov. '93) with a feature article on the Video Toaster 4000.

My wife and I have been members of our local Amiga user group, the New
Orleans Commodore Klub Amiga Group (NOCK Amiga Group) since we moved to the
area in late 1988, and we've served as officers in the club. I was the club
disk librarian for a few years before I took the job of moderator.aide on
the Amiga echo.

Carol and I enjoy reading and writing messages on Fidonet and Usenet. I
frequent the Amiga, Amiga_Video, Video (Toaster), Disney, and Disneyana
echoes on Fidonet as well as Usenet's rec.arts.disney.  I receive a few
newsletters on Internet dealing with animation, the Video Toaster and
LightWave 3D.  Carol enjoys Usenet's rec.arts.disney newsgroup, and
Fidonet's Disney, Disneyana, and Katty_Korner echoes.

One day I hope to be working for the Disney Company in Orlando, Florida or
in California.  I would want it to be a good, well-paying job -- but it
would not necessarily have to be involving graphics and animation. My
background is in television post-production and show production, and in
writing, so I think a job with Disney would be something I would be
well-suited for.  I am currently the senior graphics designer for WVUE-TV in
New Orleans.  I have had additional experience as a TV producer/director of
live entertainment and news programs, corporate videos, commercials, and
station promotion.  I've been in broadcasting for about 22 years now.

Carol and I are living in the New Orleans area.  I got interested in New
Orleans back in high school while living in Westbury, New York.  When I was
deciding where to go to college I picked Loyola University because it had
the best television facilities of any college that I could find, even in the
New York area.  I was given a partial scholarship to Loyola based upon my
academic record.  I graduated with a B. A. from Loyola with a Communications
major and an On-Air Performance minor.  Now I'm sorry that I didn't study
anything about computers there, because they had an excellent facility and
even my dorm roommate was a computer major.

I studied art in college as well as at an art school after graduation. I
continue to hone my skills both on the job at the TV station as well as at
home on my A4000 and Video Toaster.  I recommend Art Department Professional
and Pixel 3D Professional to all Toaster users.

Besides using the Amiga, our favorite hobby is anything to do with Disney. I
have been sprinkled with Pixie Dust for many years now!  My wife and I are
among the founding members of the Louiseyana Disneyana chapter (yes, that's
how the club wants to spell Louisiana!) of the National Fantasy Fan Club.
The NFFC is a group composed of Disney enthusiasts and collectors. Fidonet's
Disney and Disneyana echoes and Usenet's rec.arts.disney newsgroup have
received many of our Disneyana and Disney theme park related posts.

Our extensive trip reports about the 1st and 2nd Disneyana Conventions have
been well-received and are currently available for downloading from Steven
"The Surge!" Soria's "Mickey's Kingdom" BBS in California.

We have developed many friendships with Disney fans and "cast members"
through these networks, including people who work at Walt Disney World,
Disneyland, Disney Software, and Walt Disney Studios Feature Animation in
California.  We've met some of the friends we've made on the computer
networks when we attended the 1st and 2nd Official Disneyana Conventions
(the first at Walt Disney World and the second at Disneyland in California),
and we plan on attending the 3rd one this September in Orlando as well.  We
will also be meeting up with a lot of our Disney echo friends at the Fidonet
Disney EchoEARS Day gathering this July at Walt Disney World.  I'm the
coordinator of this event, and if it is successful it will become an annual
pilgrimage just like the Amiga Echo get-togethers are.  Both Carol and I
agree with the Disney philosophy of quality, team spirit, and a positive
attitude.

On the Disney echo I've been called "One of the EchoEARS Old Men", which is
a reference to the original team of animators that Walt Disney hired, so I
consider this quite a compliment.  Carol and I have also been dubbed "The
Den Leaders of the Fidonet Disney Echo".  On Usenet's rec.arts.disney we
were appointed into that newsgroup's fictional "Future Disney Cabinet" with
the positions of FDC Walk-Around Mickey and Minnie Mouse, which we also
consider quite an honor to be picked to represent those famous mice, even
without our asking for that position.  I am also currently known on the
Fidonet Disney echo as "Sitter on a Stool, Facing the corner person, with
silly cone bolted to Head, Keeper, Protector, & Wearer of the Disney
DuncEars Cap", a dubious honor at best.  :-)  I've also been referred to on
the Amiga echo as moderator.aide.sex.tiger...  ;-)


                Rich Koster

